Utterances.UttText: A 44-year-old male with ESRD was in his usual state of health until the day of hospitalization when he became unresponsive and pulseless during hemodialysis.

Phrases.PhraseText: was in his usual state of health

Utterances.UttText: An automated external defibrillator was placed and he received appropriate shock as well as transient CPR.
He was brought to our emergency department for further management.
His history included hypertension, hepatitis C infection, human immunodeficiency virus infection , anemia, and secondary hyperparathyroidism.
On arrival, he was hemodynamically stable and euvolemic on exam.

Initial laboratory data revealed an uncorrected calcium of 1.65 mmol/L (normal 2.12.55 mmol/L), ionized calcium of 0.71 mmol/L (normal 1.12 1.32 mmol/L), potassium of 3.2 mmol/L (normal 3.5 5.1 mmol/L), magnesium of 0.61 mmol/L (normal 0.66 0.95 mmol/L), and phosphorus of 0.97 mmol/L (normal 0.811.45 mmol/L).
Initial electrocardiogram showed a sinus rhythm with a prolonged QT interval and diffuse T-wave changes (Fig. 1a), but in minutes, he developed torsades de pointes (Fig. 1b) and became unresponsive.

Phrases.PhraseText: a sinus rhythm with a prolonged QT interval

Utterances.UttText: He was again resuscitated and transferred to the intensive care unit.

Phrases.PhraseText: transferred to the intensive care unit.

Utterances.UttText: Treatment of his secondary hyperparathyroidism had been initiated 3 years prior when his intact parathyroid hormone (iPTH) level was 117 pmol/L (normal 24.2 66.1 pmol/L) and included paricalcitol with hemodialysis and daily cinacalcet.
Three weeks prior to admission, his cinacalcet dose was increased from 60 to 90 mg daily due to an iPTH level of 85.6 pmol/L (calcium was 2.11 mmol/ L and phosphorus was 2.26 mmol/L).

Phrases.PhraseText: to 90 mg daily due to an iPTH level of 85.6 pmol/L

Utterances.UttText: Other home medications included sevelamer carbonate, nifedipine XL, and metoprolol succinate.

Utterances.UttText: On admission, cinacalcet was stopped, and magnesium , potassium, and calcium were administered.
No other factors capable of inducing hypocalcemia were identified.
The diagnosis of torsades de pointes associated with prolonged QT interval in part due to cinacalcet-induced severe hypocalcemia was made.

Phrases.PhraseText: The diagnosis of torsades de pointes
in part due to cinacalcet-induced severe hypocalcemia

Utterances.UttText: Once his total body calcium was replaced, the QT interval normalized on his electrocardiogram and no further ar-rhythmias were observed.
Phosphate binders and vitamin D sterols are the mainstay of management for secondary hyperparathyroidism in patients with ESRD.
Cinacalcet was recently introduced as an alternative option, working via the calcium sensing receptor by enhancing its sensitivity to extracellular calcium and thereby inhibiting PTH release.

Phrases.PhraseText: working via the calcium sensing receptor

Utterances.UttText: Hypocalcemia is a common adverse effect, which can potentially be mitigated by the concurrent use of calcium-based phosphate binders.

Utterances.UttText: Symptomatic hypocalcemia induced by cinacalcet is rare, and in the OPTIMA study, only 5 of patients presented with a serum calcium level less than 7.5 mg/dL (1.87 mmol/L).

Phrases.PhraseText: presented with a serum calcium level less

Utterances.UttText: Torsades de pointes, a polymorphic form of ventricular tachycardia, is seen in patients with prolonged cardiomyocyte repolarization, which is exhibited on electrocardiogram by long QT intervals.

Phrases.PhraseText: a polymorphic form of ventricular tachycardia,

Utterances.UttText: Hypocalcemia, hypokalemia, and hypomagnesemia increase risk of torsades de pointes by prolonging repolarization.

Phrases.PhraseText: hypomagnesemia increase risk of torsades de pointes

Utterances.UttText: Hypocalcemia further increases risk by potentiating development of early after depolarizations.Our patients arrhythmia did not resolve until his serum calcium level normalized, and other electrolytes were replaced.

Phrases.PhraseText: risk by potentiating development of early after depolarizations.
resolve until his serum calcium level

Utterances.UttText: To our knowledge, this may be one of the first reported cases of cinacalcet-induced hypocalcemia resulting in torsades de pointes and cardiac arrest.

Phrases.PhraseText: one of the first reported cases of cinacalcet-induced hypocalcemia

Utterances.UttText: As recommended by the pharmaceutical company, serum calcium and ionized calcium levels should be measured within 1 week after initiation or dose adjustment of cinacalcet.

Once a maintenance dose has been established, monthly monitoring of serum calcium is warranted, and the importance of adherence to oral calcium supplementation as needed should be stressed with all patients.

Abnormalities in serum potassium and magnesium(b)a EKG showing diffuse T wave abnormalities and QT interval prolongation; b cardiac monitor strips from this patient showing polymorphic ventricular tachycardia consistent with torsades de pointes might potentiate the risk for arrhythmias, and monthly monitoring of electrolytes to ensure normal serum levels of potassium and magnesium is also recommended.

Phrases.PhraseText: (b)a EKG showing diffuse T wave abnormalities

Utterances.UttText: Cinacalcet should be used cautiously in patients with known risk factors for hypocalcemia, with a history of QT prolongation, and with concurrent use of other QT prolonging agents.
